THEN and NOW

At Ker & Downey we have been refining the craft of leading safaris for 65 years and we haven’t finished yet. We design our own tents, modify our own trucks and safari vehicles and maintain everything at our Nairobi headquarters. Our crew members – some of whom are third generation camp staff – are essential to the safari experience, providing unobtrusive, skilled and attentive service.

We tailor each camp to specific people so that everything suits you, our guests. We handle all the logistics, ensuring that there are hot showers when you want them and cold drinks when you need them. When guests stay in a Ker & Downey camp they can rest assured that they have the best of everything. Falling asleep to the sounds of the bush in one of our palatial canvas tents, you will feel safe, comfortable and at one with nature.

A lone male lion was recently sighted during an early morning game dive in the Massai Mara. 

Did you know that out of all the big cats in the world, lions are the only ones that live in large groups, in a pride?

Roles within the lion pride are divided between females and males, with the females doing most of the hunting and raising the cubs. The males protect their pride and the territory against the dominant males from other surrounding prides.

Today is #WorldPangolinDay, and we wanted to shine a light on this weird, wonderful, yet endangered mammal. Recently captured on camera by guide Olo Nicklin, we encountered this pangolin while staying with guests at our Mobile Camp in the Masai Mara. 

Spotting a Pangolin is an extraordinary, rare and memorable experience - even for us guides who spend so much time in the wilderness! These elusive creatures have a tough exterior and are the only mammal with scales. A pangolin’s primary defence is to curl into a ball, making them extremely vulnerable to poaching. For this reason, these creatures are sadly becoming increasingly hard to find in the wild. 

We want to shout out to @thepangolinproject and thank them for their dedication to protecting pangolins! Through community partnerships, science and raising awareness, they are working tirelessly to identify and conserve important pangolin populations in Kenya. Head over to (www.thepangolinproject.org) to learn more about their incredible work in protecting pangolins.

The Lower Zambezi valley is a huge rift in the earth's crust, through which a mighty river flows. 

The park’s distinguishing features are the rugged escarpment to the north, the river itself, and its numerous islands, lagoons and floodplains which attract most of the Zambian wildlife. 

There are approximately 50 mammal species and 400 bird species, which thrive in the park, as well as a wide variety of spectacular trees, grasses and flowers. 

Most large mammals in the national park congregate on the floodplain, including the Cape buffalo, a large elephant population, lion, leopard, many ant elope species, crocodile and hippopo. Occasional sightings of wild dog occur.
